          "body": "Verses 12-13 are the chapter's theological and pastoral center. *Return to Me with all your heart, and with fasting, weeping and mourning; and rend your heart and not your garments*. The contrast is not against external rites — fasting and assembly are commanded in the very next verses — but against external rites detached from inward turn. Tearing the garment was the ancient Near Eastern gesture of grief and repentance (Genesis 37:34; 2 Kings 22:11); Joel exposes it as insufficient. The heart (*levav*) must be torn. And the ground of the appeal is not Israel's worthiness but Yahweh's character: *for He is gracious and compassionate, slow to anger, abounding in lovingkindness and relenting of evil* — the Exodus 34:6 self-revelation Yahweh gave Moses on Sinai, now invoked as the warrant for hope. The chapter teaches that genuine repentance always rests on who God has revealed Himself to be, not on the depth of human contrition."
